## The Milgrain Tax (There Isn't One)

Milgrain is the tiny row of beaded metal detail along the edge of a ring — the single most efficient tool for adding vintage character to a setting. The widespread assumption among buyers is that milgrain adds significant cost. This is false.

Comparing milgrain vs. non-milgrain settings of equivalent quality on Blue Nile, the milgrain premium is typically $0–$200 — less than 5% of total ring cost at any budget. Yet the visual impact of milgrain on vintage character is enormous: a milgrain-edged solitaire reads as unmistakably vintage even with no other detailing. A plain solitaire reads as modern regardless of how the band is shaped.

**The Milgrain Tax is a myth.** The real cost driver in vintage settings is the volume of accent diamonds (channel set, pavé band, halo), not the milgrain edge itself. Buyers who skip milgrain to "save money" are making a category error — they're avoiding the cheapest element and potentially spending more on accent diamonds that don't move the vintage-character needle as much.

The practical rule: if you care about vintage character, always choose milgrain over plain on an otherwise comparable setting. The cost difference is negligible; the aesthetic difference is significant.

