## The 4 Vintage Eras — Which One Is Your Ring?

**Art Deco (1920–1935):** Geometric symmetry, angular lines, baguette-cut side stones, and platinum with black enamel accents. An Art Deco oval ring will have a hexagonal or octagonal halo, step-cut trapezoid side stones, or a channel of baguettes flanking the center. Bold, architectural, architectural. Matching colors: white diamond + platinum only — yellow gold ruins the aesthetic.

**Edwardian (1901–1915):** Delicate lace-like filigree, milgrain everywhere, diamonds set in platinum over yellow gold (the first era to use platinum at scale). An Edwardian oval ring features lace-pattern bridges, scrollwork undergallery, and a sense of intricate handwork. Softer than Art Deco but more ornate. Matching colors: platinum or white gold; rose gold is a modern interpretation that works.

**Victorian (1837–1901):** Heavier, more ornate, often featuring colored gemstones (sapphires, garnets, emeralds). A Victorian-inspired oval ring will have a cluster halo, engraved gold band, six-prong cathedral head, and a sense of material richness. Yellow gold is period-correct. The Garland Sapphire setting on this list is the most Victorian option.

**Art Nouveau / Romantic (1890–1910, revived constantly):** Organic curves, floral motifs, and nature-inspired forms. The Infinity setting (the most popular in this category) falls here — its intertwining shank evokes organic growth. Enchanted Scroll, Floral Ellipse, and Pear-Shaped Diamond Detail are all Art Nouveau-adjacent. Most buyers who "want vintage" without knowing which era they want are actually describing Art Nouveau.

