## Rose Cut, Old Mine Cut & Antique Oval Diamonds — The Complete Guide

This is the section most guides skip entirely. If your search history includes "rose cut oval diamond," "old mine cut oval diamond," or "antique cut oval diamond," this section is specifically for you.

### What Is a Rose Cut Oval Diamond?

A rose cut diamond is one of the oldest diamond faceting styles in existence, first developed in the 16th century. It has a flat bottom, a domed top, and typically 12–24 triangular facets arranged in a radiating pattern. There is no culet (bottom point) and no pavilion — the diamond is essentially a dome.

When shaped into an oval outline, it becomes a **rose cut oval diamond** or **oval rose cut diamond**. The result looks dramatically different from a modern oval brilliant:

- **Less brilliant** — fewer facets catch less light; the stone glows rather than sparkles
- **More transparent** — you can often see through a rose cut to the setting beneath
- **Larger face-up appearance per carat** — the flat bottom means nearly all carat weight appears in face-up area (20–30% larger apparent size than a comparable oval brilliant)
- **Moody and atmospheric** — candlelight and warm lighting suit rose cuts far better than bright overhead LED

Rose cut ovals are NOT available on Blue Nile. They are sourced from specialty dealers: August Vintage, Erstwhile Jewelry, Trumpet & Horn, or local estate and antique dealers.

### What Is an Old Mine Cut Oval Diamond?

The "old mine cut" technically refers to a specific pre-1900 faceting style with a high crown, small table, large culet, and 58 facets — but the shape was usually round (the predecessor to the modern round brilliant). True old mine cut ovals are exceptionally rare because the oval shape itself was not standardized until the 1960s.

What buyers searching "old mine cut oval" are usually describing is either:
1. A **rose cut oval** (which is antique-faceted and oval-shaped)
2. A **modern oval brilliant** in a vintage-style setting
3. An oval **old European cut** (similar high-crown faceting but rounded square outline)

If you want something that reads as "old mine," a rose cut oval in a bezel or six-prong crown setting is the correct product.

### The Portuguese Cut Oval Diamond

The Portuguese cut (developed in the 17th century) features additional facet rows above and below the girdle — typically 72–80 facets total. When applied to an oval shape, it creates extraordinary light dispersion with a distinctly antique, complex pattern. Oval Portuguese cut diamonds are rare and expensive. They are produced by a handful of specialty cutters and are not available on Blue Nile.

### The Practical Recommendation

If you want a vintage-LOOKING ring at modern engagement ring prices: choose any setting from this guide with a modern oval brilliant diamond. You get maximum sparkle, modern certification, and the full Blue Nile return policy.

If you want the authentic antique diamond CUT (rose cut, old mine, Portuguese): budget for a specialty dealer, expect to pay 20–40% more per carat than an equivalent modern oval, and accept that the diamond will not have a GIA brilliant grading report (rose cuts are graded differently).

